# Slack human → bot reaction mirror

Use this contract when implementing or reviewing Slack `reaction_added` handling in runtime code (for example `employee-factory`). Inbound **`reaction_added` is Socket Mode on each employee**, not slack-orchestrator.

## Trigger (required)

- Inbound event is `reaction_added`.
- Reaction target item is a Slack `message` event item (not e.g. file).
- Channel id and message timestamp are non-empty (includes public channels, private channels, and DMs).
- Message belongs to the **current** bot (`item_user == bot_user_id` for this process).
- Reactor is non-empty, is **not** this bot’s user id (avoids echo when the bot adds the mirrored emoji), and is **not** a squad / multiagent bot id (`MULTIAGENT_BOT_USER_IDS`).

**Gated on:** `GeneralAutoReactionEnabledForChannel` — same Redis `general_auto_reaction_enabled` / admin “Reactions” toggle as plain-message auto-reaction (legacy open mode when the registry is empty; per-row flag when the channel is registered; off for unknown channel ids when any channel is registered).

**Not gated on:** channel allowlist enforcement for Socket Mode membership, or `owner_ids`. (Ownership-style tightening may return later.)

**Still respected:** per-channel **out of office** (registry `out_of_office_enabled`) skips handling before mirror; outbound rate limiting for posting the reaction.

## Action (required)

- For every qualifying event, **that same bot** (the message author) adds exactly one reaction to the same message.
- The bot uses the **same emoji name** Slack sent on the event (`reaction` field).

## Multi-agent note

Each employee runs as a separate Slack app / deployment. When a human reacts to **Joanne’s** message, only **Joanne’s** runtime has `item_user` matching; other squad processes ignore. Mirror is per authoring bot.

## Safety and operability

- Treat Slack `already_reacted` as success (idempotent behavior).
- Keep behavior fully non-blocking and tolerant to transient Slack failures.
- Log structured route decisions with at least: path (`reaction_mirror_human`), employee, channel, anchor timestamp, reactor user, mirrored reaction name.
